1 NOTE <p class="MsoNormal"><span lang="EN-US">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;
2 CONC  &nbsp;HOUSE FAMILY OF PERRY TWP.</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span lang="EN-US">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
2 CONC &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span lan
2 CONC g="EN-US">William Percival (Percy) House was born in Huntsville on December 9, 1883.&nbsp; On that day, he became the foster child of William Henry House (1832-1886) and his wife Mary Ann Dingman (184
2 CONC 4-1898) of Con. 5 Chaffey Twp.&nbsp; When Percy was just two years old, his foster father died and his foster mother married James Aaron Prince (1848-1933).&nbsp; Percy had just turned 15 years of age
2 CONC  when his foster mother passed away and he then became the temporary ward of his step-foster father.&nbsp; Even by late 19<sup>th</sup> Century standards, he had a very difficult start to his life whi
2 CONC ch undoubtedly shaped his character.</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span lang="EN-US">As a young man, Percy worked as a farm labourer and,
2 CONC  in 1903, found employment with William and Julia Ann Bice of Perry Twp. (Lots 26 &amp; 27 Con. 5).&nbsp; The following spring on May 24, 1904, Percy married their young widowed daughter, Lillie Hazel
2 CONC  Croft (b. 27 July 1882 Uxbridge, Ont.).&nbsp; Lillie already had three infant daughters from her first marriage with John William Croft: Charlotte Annie Croft (1899); Olive Viola May Croft (1900); an
2 CONC d Vietta Winnifred Croft (1902).&nbsp; The two oldest girls were born in Perry Twp. and, until 1912, lived with their maternal grandparents in Perry and then in Uxbridge.</span></p>
<p class="MsoNorm
2 CONC al"><span lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span lang="EN-US">Percy and Lillie began their married life in Perry Twp.&nbsp; Percy farmed and logged in both Perry and Chaffey Twp. a
2 CONC nd the family moved frequently.&nbsp; About 1920, Percy was a teamster foreman delivering logs and firewood by horse-drawn sleds from the Sand Lake (Oudaze Lake) mill to the Novar train station.</span
2 CONC ></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span lang="EN-US">Percy and Lillie had six children: Hazel Elizabeth (1905-1999); Velma Louise (1908-1992); Will
2 CONC iam Elias (1910-1969); Elgin Bernard (1912-1961); Gertrude Mildred (Millie) (1915-2001); and Ethel Genevive Irene (1920-1993).&nbsp; Their first three children were born in Perry Twp.</span></p>
<p c
2 CONC lass="MsoNormal"><span lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span lang="EN-US">About 1924, the House family moved from the Novar area to Huntsville where they remained.&nbsp; Throughou
2 CONC t his adult life, Percy invested in real estate and, as a result, the family lived in many different houses.&nbsp; For a short period, Percy owned a second-hand goods store in Huntsville but continued
2 CONC  doing business long after the store was closed.&nbsp; Lillie was a midwife and during the 1940s and 50s, Lillie and Percy raised a foster child. </span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span lang="EN-US">&
2 CONC nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span lang="EN-US">In 1961, Percy and Lillie tragically lost their younger son which weighed heavily on them.&nbsp; Less than a year after Elgin&rsquo;s death, L
2 CONC illie passed away in Huntsville on February 26, 1962.&nbsp; Percy wed Hannah Wreggett on October 5, 1963 and he died in Huntsville on June 7, 1968.</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span lang="EN-US">
2 CONC &nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span lang="EN-US">The children of Percy and Lillie: Hazel wed Earl R. Vincent and resided in Bracebridge; Velma married William G. Young and lived mainly in Hu
2 CONC ntsville; William wed Edna May Jacobs and they resided in Toronto; Elgin married Emma Ida Peeler and lived in Chaffey and Huntsville; Millie wed Stephen Branch and resided on Savage Settlement Road in
2 CONC  Perry and, after Steve&rsquo;s passing, she married George Lindup and lived in Novar; Ethel wed Howard Jacobs and resided in Toronto.</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span lang="EN-US
2 CONC ">&nbsp;</span></p>
