The Brethren Trout (Traut)
by Noel Trout, © 2000
Date: November 23, 2000 at 09:43:13
xmas
2 CONC cat1@aol.com

Upon investigating early TROUT family origins in America, descendants
can typically trace their family back to either one of two seminal
TROUT lines. The most well-known and documented l
2 CONC ine is the Wendel
TRAUT line, which arrived in America in 1738. One of the most
scholarly and source-supported books I have read on this particular
line is the book 250 Year History of my Trout Family
2 CONC . This book was
written by George Egbert Trout (1913-1999). I was able to purchase one
of the last remaining copies before the author passed away. At that
time, his grandson-Matthew Curtis-posted a me
2 CONC ssage on the Trout
Genealogical Forum, "I have the last 30 copies of his book and I will
be selling them for the family. Please e-mail me directly if you are
interested" (mattnmona@earthlink.net). The
2 CONC  other TROUT line, and the
focus of this essay, is the less well-known Brethren TRAUT line, which
arrived in America in 1719. (Author’s note: I will switch back and
forth between TRAUT, the original
2 CONC  German variation of the surname, and
TROUT, the Americanized variation of the surname).

First, I will give some background on the other line-the Wendel TRAUT
line. According to the aforementioned bo
2 CONC ok by George E. TROUT, the
Wendel TRAUT line begins with the patriarch himself, his full name
being Johann Wendel George TRAUT (1689-1760). He immigrated to
America, arriving in Philadelphia in 1738. 
2 CONC He brought with him four
daughters and at least three sons: Hans George (b. 1725), Hans
Nicklaus (1727-1753), and Hans Michael (1730-1780). They all settled
into the Strasburg Township area of Lancast
2 CONC er County, Pennsylvania. In
1752, two of his sons-George and Niclaus-left Lancaster County and
moved to Virginia. Niclaus moved to Augusta County and was
accidentally killed by a shotgun blast shortly
2 CONC  thereafter. George
moved to Rockingham County, leaving descendants in the Roanoke area,
and he may have eventually made it to North Carolina. The third
son-Michael-stayed in Lancaster County until af
2 CONC ter his father’s death.
Around 1771 he and his family moved to Frederick County, Maryland.
Wendel TRAUT’s first wife had died before the family came to America
so a year after his arrival, he marr
2 CONC ied another woman in the Strasburg
Township. They had at least four daughters and two sons: Johan Paul
(1739-1794) and Wendel II (1743-1820). It looks like Johan Paul stayed
in Lancaster County while 
2 CONC Wendel II moved to York County,
Pennsylvania. Finally, it must be noted that the patriarch, Wendel I,
had a cousin who had immigrated to America prior to him in 1733. His
name was Hans Martin TRAUT (b
2 CONC . 1677) and he settled in Berks County,
Pennsylvania. He brought with him at least three daughters and two
sons: Johan Debalt (1706-1738) and John Henry (1718-1746). The latter
son ended up moving to 
2 CONC Frederick County, Maryland, just like his
half-brother Michael. All of Wendel’s and Hans Martin’s children had
their own children in the areas noted above, and this TRAUT family
began to spread th
2 CONC roughout Pennsylvania and Virginia.

While Wendel’s family is more well-documented, there is another TROUT
family that arrived earlier. This is the family that is referred to in
the 1903 book, Some 
2 CONC Virginia Families by Hugh Milton McIlhany, Jr.
This book is one of the earliest and most well-known TROUT family
history books, and gives many details about descendants from this
other TROUT family. H
2 CONC owever, the book cannot pinpoint the exact
origins of this family, only stating that, "From the traditions
preserved in several branches of the Trout family today, it would seem
that many years before
2 CONC  the Revolutionary War three brothers,
Lutherans, fleeing from religious persecution in Germany, emigrated
from the neighborhoood of Frankfort-on-the-Main and settled in
Germantown, Philidelphia." The
2 CONC  book goes on to state that family
tradition has it that the three brothers’ names were Nathaniel,
Daniel, and Jeremiah. The author states that while the traditional
account of this family’s histo
2 CONC ry is "in the main correct…the names of
the original immigrants have been handed down inaccurately." Instead,
the names of the three brothers were John Balthazar (aka Baltzer),
George, and Jeremias 
2 CONC Trout, and the book picks up with an account of
their lives and descendants beginning around 1740.

If one were only to rely upon the well-known text Some Virginia
Families, it would seem that the exa
2 CONC ct details of this family’s
genesis in America have been lost to antiquity. However, there are
other, less well-known texts that exist, which I believe give a more
detailed and accurate account of j
2 CONC ust who these initial TROUTs were.
These books detail the history of the Church of the Brethren, which
began in Germany in 1708. The Church of the Brethren (also known as
the "Dunkers") was what could
2 CONC  be considered an outlaw sect in Germany
at the time. As a result of great persecution, 20 members of this
small religious congregation left for America in 1719, eight of whom
were TRAUTs, and they la
2 CONC nded in Philadelphia, settling in Germantown.
One of the earliest books that detailed this church’s history is
Martin Brumbaugh’s A History of the German Baptist Brethren in Europe
and America, pu
2 CONC blished in 1899. Another Brethren church historian
whose books include these earliest TROUT ancestors is Donald F.
Durnbaugh (see source footnotes for specific texts). Finally, a TROUT
descendant and 
2 CONC another Brethren church historian and author is Ellen
Louise Larick, whom I have gotten to know and found very helpful and
knowledgeable (she has even traveled to Germany to research the
origins of th
2 CONC is TROUT family; more on that further below).

According to these various texts about the history of the Church of
the Brethren, of the eight TRAUT family members who made the trek to
America in 1719 
2 CONC with 12 other Brethren congregants, the adult men
consisted of three brothers. Their names were Johann Henrich, Georg
Balthasar, and Jeremias TRAUT. The names of these three brothers as
recorded in th
2 CONC e Church of the Brethren history is strikingly similar
to those mentioned in the McIlhany’s Some Virginia Families book. All
three brothers were from Frankenthal, Germany.[1] Again, this is very
sim
2 CONC ilar to the fuzzy traditional account documented by McIlhany
("Frankfort-on-the-Main"), as is the fact that the three brothers
immigrated here in the pursuit of religious freedom. These original
three
2 CONC  TRAUT brothers settled in the vicinity of Philadelphia County,
Pennsylvania. However, while the details of the very initial history
of this family coming to America are preserved, once they arrived i
2 CONC n
America it becomes very difficult to determine who their offspring
were. Apparently, many of their children bore the same name as the
original three brothers, probably in honor of each other. It bec
2 CONC omes
impossible to tell, for example, when a land grant states that Baltzer
TROUT owned property in Germantown, Philadelphia in 1734,[3] whether
this was the original Baltzer or one of the many descen
2 CONC dants who
retained the Baltzer namesake. Further complicating this puzzle is the
confusion over Johann Henrich or John Henry (see further below). In
some ways it appears that the three brothers may ha
2 CONC ve been the
children of a man by the same name. One day I hope to stumble upon
some new pieces of information that will shed light on this mystery.

Nevertheless, let me go back to the beginning in Ge
2 CONC rmany and then onto
Philadelphia, and I will give as full account of the origins of this
TROUT line as I can. Some of this comes from the aforementioned
Brethren history texts while other information 
2 CONC is pieced together from
other sources (see footnotes to determine what comes from where). Not
surprising for genealogical research, not all of the pieces fit.
However, I wanted to give as full account
2 CONC  as possible of all the
information that I could find in hopes that someone else with other or
new information might be able to eventually put things together in
their right or complete order.

To sta
2 CONC rt off with, in Germany during the late 1600s and early 1700s,
there was the state-mandated form of Christianity and then there were
other illegal denominations or "Pietists." One such group was the
A
2 CONC nabaptists. They believed that infant baptism was not valid; an
adult, in the understanding of his or her own mature mind, must make a
decision to follow Christ and then be baptized. Thus came about t
2 CONC heir
name "Anabaptist": in other words, re-baptizers. As uncontroversial as
it may sound today, this was a crime punishable by hard labor, prison,
or banishment. Part of the problem was that all of th
2 CONC ese sects were a
challenge to the church-state’s prevailing viewpoints and consequently
their power. While certain groups, like the "Inspirationists," made
dramatic prophecies in which they "denounc
2 CONC ed the wickedness of the
authorities,"[4] the Brethren were not as exciting. They were
considered merely troublesome by the authorities "only because of
their belief in the necessity of baptism by imm
2 CONC ersion."[4]

In 1705 a Johann Henrich TRAUT was one of four citizens of Lambsheim
(near Frankenthal), Germany, imprisoned for their refusal to swear
oaths of allegience.[1] In 1706, a Johannes TRAUT w
2 CONC as accused of
Pietism in Lambsheim Rheinland/Pfalz and sentenced to cleaning the
town’s ditches.[2] This may have been the same Johann Henrich TRAUT
that was one of our original three brothers or it
2 CONC  may have been the
father of all three. Records show that he was married to Anna
Katharina and had two sons, aged 10 and 6 at the time;[2] a daughter
and a son-in-law also were living with him.[1] At 
2 CONC any rate, some
records state that he sold his home in Lambsheim in 1709 and went to
London, England.[1] He was 40 years old at this time.[2] Later on, he
sailed to New York and then settled into the D
2 CONC ublin Township of
Montgomery C
