1 NOTE 20 Jan 1724/5 - Hans Georg Traut born, Kleinfischlingen, near Landau, Rheinland Pfalz, Germany.

5 Sep 1738 - Hans Georg Traut, age12, arrives in Philadelphia with widower father, Johann Wendel Georg 
2 CONC Traut ("Wintell Draut"), who  takes oath of allegiance at Philadelphia after having sailed on the Winter Gally (Hope Shipping Company), commanded by Edward Painter.  Source: List 52-A, Pennsylvania Ge
2 CONC rman Pioneers, Ralph B. Strassberger and William J. Hinke (1934), pp. 198-204.

1739 - Hans Georg Traut, father Johann Wendel Georg Traut and family, living in Strasburg (current Paradise) Twp, near S
2 CONC trasburg, Lancaster, PA by this time.

13 Oct 1748 - Hans Georg Traut's younger brother, Hans Nicholas Trout, applies for a land warrant for 137.5 acres in Bart Twp, Lancaster, PA, just south of Mine 
2 CONC Hill.  Here, it is believed, Hans Georg (age 23), Hans Nicholas (age 21), and younger brother Hans Michol (age 18) lived until 1752 when brothers Hans Georg and Hans Nicholas moved on to Virginia and 
2 CONC left younger brother Hans Michol in charge of the home farm.  Source: Geo. E. Trout, 250 Year History of My Trout Family (privately printed, Closson Press, Apollo, PA, 1991), p. 18.

>>Transaction det
2 CONC ails: Land warrant  #124 dated 13 Oct 1748, survey dated 29 Nov 1757, recorded in C-11-71.

>>Locator note: Lands would have been 4.8 miles ESE of Strasburg, just north of SR 896.  Exact location woul
2 CONC d have been N39 57.77'; W76 5.69' (NAD 27), USGS 7.5' Gap, PA quad.  Site first visited in October, 1999.

1 July 1752 - Younger brother Hans Nicholas Traut purchases 145 acres on the Shenandoah River
2 CONC , Augusta County, VA from Christophel Franciscus of Lancaster Borough, Lancaster, PA.  Source: Augusta deeds 4:433, 4:435.  Also see Geo. E. Trout, 250 Year History of My Trout Family, (privately prin
2 CONC ted, Closson Press, Apollo, PA,1991), p. 18.

>>Locator note: The deed language places the lands on Cub Run near the base of Peaked Mountain (now called Massahutten Mountain) near the current village 
2 CONC of Montevideo, Rockingham, VA, which was part of Augusta County at the time.  Rockingham County was later erected 20 Oct 1777.  In more exact terms, the general Montevideo area is located at N38 13', 
2 CONC W78 27' (NAD 27), USGS 7.5' Grottoes, VA quad.  Site first visited in October, 1999.

>>Ed. note: Christopher Franciscus of Lancaster County had bought 3100 acres of land in Augusta County, Virginia f
2 CONC rom Jacob Stover in 1740.  Approximately 9 years later, during the period of 1749-1750, Franciscus started selling this land to other Pennsylvania Germans, with the 2 July 1752 sale to Hans Nicholas T
2 CONC raut being among these numerous out sales (research note courtesy of Jack Gross, his cite 144-1).

1752 - Hans Georg Traut, together with younger brother Hans Nicholas Traut, moves from Bart Twp, Lanc
2 CONC aster, PA, to Augusta County, VA.  Younger brother Michol stays behind and farms the tract in Bart Twp.  Source: Geo. E. Trout, 250 Year History of My Trout Family, (privately printed, Closson Press, 
2 CONC Apollo, PA, 1991), p. 18.

>>Ed. note: Emerging research circumstantially suggests that younger brother, Johan Deobalt Traut, age 18, also accompanied Hans Nicholas and Hans Georg to Augusta County, V
2 CONC A.

22 Nov 1753 - After the accidental shooting death of younger brother Hans Nicholas Traut, Hans Georg Traut is named administrator and settles his brother's estate.  (For details of the accidental 
2 CONC shooting accident, see notes for Hans Nicholas Traut.)  Source: Augusta will book 2:4

6 Dec 1753 - Sale of Nicholas Trout's estate to Jno. Love; Jno. Hales; Patrick Wilson; Jno. Walles; Valentine Pen
2 CONC ce; Wm. Logan; Gasper Faught; Jacob Sink; Andw. Faught; Evan Evans; Pat. Kinney; widow Trout, Nicholas Millberry; Thos. Crawford; and Geo. Trout.  Source: Augusta will book 3:447

7 May 1754 - Hans Ge
2 CONC org Traut has 324 acres surveyed in Augusta County, VA.  Source: Augusta County VA surveyors book 1:72

>>Ed. note: This would appear to be the tract later patented to Hans Georg Traut on 14 Feb 1761,
2 CONC  being comprised of 324 acres of land on both sides of South River at the mouth of Paines Run and laying immediately to the west of adjoining lands of Christian Clemons who had lived at this location 
2 CONC since 1745.  These lands were about 4 miles south of the future county line with Rockingham County, which was set aside from parent Augusta County on 20 Oct 1777.  Also see patent entry and locator no
2 CONC te for 14 Feb 1761, and sale of property on 19 Aug 1765.

c. 1754 - Hans Georg Traut, age about 29, marries Mary Clemons, age about 20, daughter of neighbor Christian Clemons.  There was a very strong
2 CONC  and enduring relationship with the Christian Clemons family, including Georg Trout &  "wife" being named in his will.  George Trout and wife Mary are also named in the probate files of Johan Paull Vo
2 CONC gt, father of Christian Clemons's wife, Catherine Vogt.

>>Ed. note: Emerging research suggests that Hans Georg's younger brother, Johan Deobalt Traut, may well have been the "unknown Trout" that marr
2 CONC ied Mary Clemon's younger sister, Catherine in about 1754 or 1755.

1755 - George Trout and Christian Clemons, Jr. are listed as present to "procession" the lines of the glebe for both his father-in-l
2 CONC aw Christian Clemons' lands boundaries and his own.

c. 1755 - (son) George Trout, Jr., is born on Paines Run, Augusta, VA.

>>Ed. note: Researcher Max Burton Trout refers to this George Trout, Jr., a
2 CONC s ìPendleton George,î to differentiate him from his father, Hans Georg Traut, who he refers to as ìBuffalo George,î both designators being based on where father and son ultimately settled in North
2 CONC  Carolina.

10 Aug 1756 - George Trout listed as a member of Captain Allen's Company of Augusta County Militia.  Other members of same company include father-in-law Christian Clemons, and neighbors Th
2 CONC omas Turk, Robert Craig (local grist mill operator), George Patterson, and Thomas Craig.  This militia service was during the French & Indian War.

19 May 1758 - A court of inquiry is held regarding t
2 CONC he circumstances of French & Indian forces burning nearby Fort Sybert on the South Branch (fairly close to the George Trout / Christian Clemons) lands, and later actions in the field by Abraham Smith'
2 CONC s Company of Augusta County Militia.

