>>Ed. note: This tract ha
2 CONC d been surveyed for Han Georg Traut on 7 May 1754, and was patented to him on 14 Feb 1761.  These lands were located on the west side of father-in-law Christian Clemons' tract.

>>Pending research: Th
2 CONC e Berger (Barger) family appears to have a number of ties to the Traut and Clemons families.  Elizabeth Clemons had married Philip Berger in about 1760.  Also in 1760, Hans Georg Traut was an appraise
2 CONC r for the Casper Barger estate, and  then in 1765, Hans Georg Traut and wife Mary sell their lands on Paines Run to Margaret Berger.  While the significance (if any) of this relationship is not yet cl
2 CONC ear, it begs further inquiry.

19 Aug 1765 - Hans Georg Traut purchases another 100 acres of land at mouth of Paines Run from Robert, Margaret, and Thomas Turk for 40 pounds.  This tract had been pate
2 CONC nted to Robert Turk on 10 Sep 1755.  Source: Augusta deeds 12:57 and 12:58.

>>Note on Augusta County deeds: Nearly all deeds of this time frame were recorded twice.  The first deed would be dated wit
2 CONC h the effective sale date, and a second deed, generally providing remedies in the event of default or misrepresentation, would be dated the very next day.  In some cases, both deeds were actually reco
2 CONC rded on the second date, but in other cases, were recorded months or years later, or if not recorded at all, simply acknowledged in the chain-of-title language of a later deed.  To clarify any possibl
2 CONC e confusion on deed dates, my entries report the actual effective sale date from the first deed in each two-deed sequence, while Lyman Chalkley in his monumental three-volume work, Chronicle of the Sc
2 CONC otch-Irish Settlement in Virginia (Baltimore, Genealogical Publishing, 1965), tends to only cite the "recording date," which is often the same as the date of the second deed in the two-deed sequence. 
