c. 8 Dec 1777 - Paul Trout is noted in ìA True Accít of Militia Draught Made in East End of Strou
2 CONC sburg Township; Capt. John Slaymakerís Company (3rd Company); Paul Trout is listed in 4th Class; brother Wendle Trout is listed in 6th Class.  List is believed to be dated on or about 8 Dec 1777 base
2 CONC d on other nearby lists in series.  Source: PA State Archives, Series 5, Volume VII, pg. 649.

>>Ed. note: The term ìclassî was used in militia organizations to designate revolving states of readine
2 CONC ss, and were typically numbered 1-8, but with some very large units occasionally having as many as 10 classes.  Members in a designated class would be the first to be called out, then at the end of th
2 CONC e designated readiness period, say 30 days, would rotate down to the bottom of the revolving readiness list, and the next class would then advance to the first call-out readiness status.  Having 8 cla
2 CONC sses also promoted fairness, in that members would not be at the first call-out readiness level during the same months each consecutive year, but instead would evolve through various months over a sev
2 CONC eral year period, thereby not causing repeated hardships during planting or harvest seasons.

>>Research Caveat: Note that in the following series of militia service entries, Paul Trout, and sometimes
2 CONC  his brother Wendle, are at various times listed under commands of Captain Mathias Slaymaker and Captain Alexander White.  It appears that the command passed back and forth between these noted individ
2 CONC uals.  It was common practice in many militia units to elect their company grade officers for set periods of time, and that may be the case in this instance.  Research continues in an effort to confir
2 CONC m that these entries are all for the same Paul Trout.

