1 NOTE <p>The obituary lists the initials J.E., these are also my initials.  Was I </p><p>named after this man? Mother was born in '18, was only four when he died </p><p>could she have known him? His first n
2 CONC ame is JAMES. Second?</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>James and Catherine had a total of 14 children.  Three of the children </p><p>died while infants and two others in early childhood.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>    ----
2 CONC ----------------------</p><p>PT.HOPE'S OLDEST PIONEER HAS PASSED</p><p>    --------------------------</p><p>J.E.MILES WAS ONE OF FIRST</p><p>FOUR MEN TO SETTLE IN</p><p>PORT HOPE</p><p>    ---------</
2 CONC p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>  In the passing of J. E. Miles, Porthope loses on of its very first </p><p>settlers, in fact one of the first four men who went to Port Hope to live </p><p>in pioneer daysm the othe
2 CONC r being Messrs W. H. Stafford, Jenness and </p><p>Haywood, who passed on some years ago.  Mr. Miles came to Pt. Hope when a </p><p>boy os sixteen and lived ther nearly 65 years; had he lived until May
2 CONC , he </p><p>would have celebrated his 81st birthday.  He superintended the </p><p>construction of the first dock at Pt. Hope in 1858.  Of Mr. Miles it may </p><p>justly be said that he was a man of st
2 CONC erling character, honorable, kind </p><p>and true; a loyal friend and an exemplary husband and father.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>   Deceased was born in New York state in 1841.  He was married to Miss </p><p
2 CONC >Catherine Leighton at Pt. Hope in 1861.  Eleven children wre born to them, </p><p>of whom ten survive; they are; Mrs. John Arnot, Alberta; Mrs. Arthur </p><p>Fisher,Denver; Mrs James Fisher, Harbor B
2 CONC each; Mrs. C. Wittman, Detroit; </p><p>Mrs. E. Kipp, Lexington; William of Flint, Theodore of Sask; Charles of </p><p>Port Huron and Eber and Mrs. Calev Richardson of Port Hope.</p><p>   Funeral servi
2 CONC ces wer conducted by Rev. Lomas from the M. E. Church </p>Tuestay afternoon.
