2 CONC Living on private means at 71 Purser's Cross Road, Fulham, married 37 years, all 7 children still alive. Son Herbert Walter still at home age 12, scholar. Also living with them Fanny Elizabeth Schofie
2 CONC ld, James's elder intellectually-impaired sister age 67.</span></p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; line-height: normal;"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: 'Microso
2 CONC ft Sans Serif','sans-serif';">1931 Haldane Road, Fulham where he had a photographic Dark Room set up under the stairs. At this time also, the couple were active in the Baptist Church, James being a Ve
2 CONC stryman and Louisa prominent in the Ladies Sewing Circle. (taken from his obituary)<br /></span></p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; line-height: normal;"><span style="font-
2 CONC size: 12pt; font-family: 'Microsoft Sans Serif','sans-serif';">1932&nbsp;&nbsp; Gave Brass standard lamp to Aubrey Kent and Ethel Brown as a wedding gift.</span></p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal" style="
2 CONC margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; line-height: normal;">(Newspaper report of their wedding)</p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; line-height: normal;">&nbsp;</p></p><p><p class="MsoNo
2 CONC rmal" style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; line-height: normal;"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: 'Microsoft Sans Serif','sans-serif';">Around this time occasional visits to her grandparents were
2 CONC  recalled by Marion, younger daughter of James Henry Schofield, recorded by her son, James Boutwood shortly before she died. Thanks to Jim for this.<br /></span></p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal" style="
2 CONC margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; line-height: normal;"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: 'Microsoft Sans Serif','sans-serif';">&nbsp;</span></p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: 0.000
2 CONC 1pt; line-height: normal;"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: 'Microsoft Sans Serif','sans-serif';">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; "Beyond this [immediate f
2 CONC amily] circle was another, my Grandparents on my father's side and&nbsp; a great concourse of uncles, aunts and cousins. They all lived in London or the suburbs so we did not see them often. I found t
2 CONC hem all rather intimidating, partly because they seemed to belong to a sort of closed shop of which I was not a member, and I sensed a slight air of disapproval when we were with them. I think that th
2 CONC ey did not approve of my mother, who seemed to them to be flighty, extravagant and superior. In fact my father obviously had a much larger income than any other member of the family, and could well af
2 CONC ford the different life-style which my mother's inclinations demanded. Although I know that this is not a matter of actual childhood memory, I was undoubtedly aware at the time of the disapproval, and
2 CONC  even small children can be very quick to sense an atmosphere and to make a good guess at the reasons for it.</span></p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; line-height: normal;
2 CONC "><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: 'Microsoft Sans Serif','sans-serif';">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; "Our visits to these grandparents always took plac
2 CONC e on a Sunday; there seemed to me a great many people to face - overwhelming aunts, strange uncles (the moustachy kisses of one of these was the ultimate horror) and among all these, a character known
2 CONC  as 'funny Auntie'. She was my grandfather's sister, and had had meningitis as a child which had left her mentally retarded. She was short and stout and her face was like a softened wax candle - expre
2 CONC ssionless except for the little dark darting eyes, which skimmed round the table like a pair of bluebottles. She had a vast appetite, and would eat quantities of bread and butter, slab cake and jam ta
2 CONC rts, then, as the last mouthful disappeared, bob a series of curtseys to the assembled company, and disappear to her room. My grandparents' house was in a quiet side street in Fulham (Haldane Road). T
2 CONC here was a Yucca in the front garden and a very small yard and garden at the back of the house which was full of potted plants.&nbsp; Downstairs the house was dark and stuffy, the living/dining room w
2 CONC as cluttered with large furniture, the kitchen smelt of gas and under the stairs my grandfather had fitted up a dark room, for he was a very keen photographer. Upstairs, however, was quite different; 
2 CONC a large drawing room took up the full width of the house, with two big windows which went down to floor level. This was a sunny room, made more so by a yellowish carpet, and a piano, small tables and 
2 CONC chairs, all of which were made of some light golden-coloured wood."</span></p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; line-height: normal;"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-famil
