1 NOTE <p><div><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml>  <o:DocumentProperties>   <o:Version>14.00</o:Version>  </o:DocumentProperties>  <o:OfficeDocumentSettings>   <o:AllowPNG/>  </o:OfficeDocumentSettings> </xml><![endif
2 CONC ]-->James William Schofield was born 22<sup>nd</sup> October 1815 in Salford, Lancs, to James Scho(l)field and Susannah, nee Eastwood.&nbsp; He was baptized 12<sup>th</sup> May 1816 at Manchester Cath
2 CONC edral. He was apprenticed in Manchester to Whitford Engineers, and moved from Manchester down to London when he was twenty, virtually penniless. According to the obituary in the Fulham Chronicle, 15th
2 CONC  Nov 1907,&nbsp; "He was appointed Foreman at Nine Elms Locomotive works and afterwards was the Foreman at Christy's Flour Mills, Lot's Road".</div></p><p><p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;At first he lived 
2 CONC in Vauxhall, Lambeth, then crossed the river to Fulham/Chelsea. Nothing is known of the courtship between him and Fanny Wyatt, but Fanny was only 18 when their son William James was born, so her paren
2 CONC ts may have withheld permission for the couple to marry.&nbsp; A second child, Fanny Elizabeth was born on 16<sup>th</sup> January 1843, both children being baptized on 23<sup>rd</sup> April 1843 at S
2 CONC t Mary&rsquo;s Lambeth and the couple finally married on 29<sup>th</sup> August 1843 at St Saviour&rsquo;s Southwark when Fanny was nearly 21.</p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal">At this time the couple we
2 CONC re living at 13, Vauxhall Walk, Lambeth, and Fanny gave birth to a third child, John, on 31<sup>st</sup> August 1844; he subsequently died age 4 yrs 11 months on 27<sup>th</sup> July 1849. Another son
2 CONC  James was born 10<sup>th</sup> May 1846, dying under 4 months on 5<sup>th</sup> September 1846.</p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal">Edward was born 2<sup>nd</sup> October 1847 only to die a few days befor
2 CONC e his elder brother John, on 19<sup>th</sup> July 1849 aged 1 year 9 months. This may have been an epidemic &ndash; diseases were common in the summer months close to the River Thames.</p></p><p><p cl
2 CONC ass="MsoNormal">More success with the girls: Elizabeth Schofield was born 27<sup>th</sup> June 1849, (just a few days before the death of her two brothers). Another son James was born 29<sup>th</sup> 
2 CONC March 1851, just in time to appear in the 1851 Census, and possibly, at about 3 months,&nbsp; the youngest child to attend the Great Exhibition of 1851.</p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal">Another son <spa
2 CONC n style="display: none;">&nbsp;Census, and possibly the youngest child to attend the Great Exhibition of 1851.</span>John was born 3<sup>rd</sup> November 1852 only to die at 1 year on 11<sup>th</sup>
2 CONC  November 1853; followed by Rebecca, on 26<sup>th</sup> March 1853, by which time the family had moved from St Thomas&rsquo;s Street to 1, Pools Lane, Chelsea. The street is still there, but now redev
2 CONC eloped into trendy townhouses. Another John, this time John Kershaw Schofield was born on 21<sup>st</sup> August 1856, the first in the Schofield dynasty as far as I am aware to bear the name Kershaw 
2 CONC which I suppose to have come from the fact that James' elder sister had married a John Kershaw. Was he perhaps in some way a family benefactor?</p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal">Susannah perhaps named fo
2 CONC r her grandma, Susannah Eastwood, was born 23<sup>rd</sup> August 1858 followed by Philip, born 15<sup>th</sup> Feb 1860, fated to die only 3 days later.</p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal">By the 1861 Cen
2 CONC sus, the family still lived at 1, Poole&rsquo;s Lane, Chelsea: James age 45 was an Engineer foreman and so was eldest son William, age 19. Five other children were in the family home, while 18 year ol
2 CONC d Fanny Elizabeth is found as a live-in servant at 11 Edith Grove with the Payne family. Shortly after the Census the family increased by one more with the birth of Hester on&nbsp; 24<sup>th</sup> May
2 CONC  1861, followed by Albert, 14<sup>th</sup> March 1863, and Victoria Alexandria Schofield the last child, 25<sup>th</sup> January 1866.</p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal">About 1869, James retired from act
2 CONC ive industrial work at age 54, and developed an interest in parochial work</p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal">When the 1871 Census was taken, William had married and left home, but 28 year old Fanny was b
2 CONC ack with the family. The intellectual impairment caused by meningitis when she was a baby was going to mean that all her life she would be living with one or other of the family.</p></p><p><p class="M
2 CONC soNormal">Other family members still at home are Elizabeth age 21, James 20, Rebecca 17, John 14, Susanna 12, Hester 9, Albert 8, and Victoria 5. The address is now given as Pool Lane, Chelsea.</p></p
2 CONC ><p><p class="MsoNormal">Around this time the houses at Schofield Terrace were being developed. It would appear that originally they were a ground floor shop with families living at the back and above
2 CONC , since the residents have a variety of trades such as Carpenter, Grocer, China Dealer, Eel Pie Shop Keeper, Watchmaker, Butcher and Printer and Stationer. As time goes on, the address is changed from
2 CONC  Schofield Terrace to 620-638 King&rsquo;s Road, though the name Schofield Terrace is clearly visible still today high up on the wall of the end house, and today the houses appear to be residences onl
2 CONC y.</p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal">James and the family moved into no 628 around 1873.</p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal">During these years, apart from his building interests, James was an ardent Liberal,
2 CONC  founder of Fulham Liberal Club and Institute in 1866, a Fulham Vestryman, Guardian of the Poor for 15 years, elected Vice-Chair 16<sup>th</sup> April 1877, on the Fulham District Board of Works, and 
2 CONC Chairman of the Peterborough Benevolent Society.</p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal">In the 1881 census the address for the Schofield Family is 628 King&rsquo;s Road, and the family consists of James, now 
2 CONC described as a Guardian of the Poor, Fulham Union and wife Fanny and daughters Fanny, Elizabeth, Susanna, Hester and Victoria. The only son still at home is Albert, age 18, Engineer&rsquo;s apprentice
2 CONC .</p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal">In 1884, James made a will disposing of his estate and providing for his wife, though she was in fact to pre-decease him, and the will would be altered several times.<
2 CONC /p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size: 8.5pt; font-family: 'Microsoft Sans Serif','sans-serif';">12 Dec 1884, The London Standard on p 3 reported: The following resolution was adopted 
2 CONC at a meeting of the Liberal Council representing the districts forming the new borough of Fulham held last night at the Eustace Hall, Walham Green, on the motion of Mr James Schofield, seconded by Gen
2 CONC eral Downes, C.B.,&nbsp; "That this Council requests Mr J F B Firth, M.P., to become the Liberal Candidate for the new borough of Fulham, and promises to use all its efforts to secure his election." <
2 CONC br /></span></p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size: 8.5pt; font-family: 'Microsoft Sans Serif','sans-serif';">24 Dec 1884 in "The Morning Post, p5" it was reported that "A meeting of t
2 CONC he Liberal Club of the new borough of Fulham was held on Monday evening at the Eustace Hall, Walham Green - Mr James Schofield in the chair - Mr Firth's letter stating his decision to stand for North 
2 CONC Kensington having been read, it was resolved that another meeting of the council be convened early next month to consider further the selection of a candidate. <br /></span></p></p><p><p class="MsoNor
2 CONC mal"><span style="font-size: 8.5pt; font-family: 'Microsoft Sans Serif','sans-serif';">25 Dec 1884 p.3 in The London Standard's report was much the same, adding "Meanwhile nominations be sent in to th
2 CONC e honorary secretary at 84 Gloucester Road, S.W.</span></p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal">In 1886, he founded the Fulham Liberal Club and Institute, Britannia Road, Fulham.</p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal"
2 CONC >In the 1891 census at 628 King&rsquo;s Road were living James &ndash; retired engineer age 75, Fanny age 68 and Victoria age 25. Victoria married in 1892, and in 1897 on 7<sup>th</sup> August, Fanny 
2 CONC succumbed to dropsy, and was buried on August 11th in Fulham Cemetery.</p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal"><strong>JAMES SCHOFIELD and ELIZA RUST</strong></p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal">On 1st&nbsp; March 
2 CONC 1898 James married next-door neighbour Eliza Rust nee Wilson, widow of Henry Rust, Carpenter, who had died some time after the 1891 Census. They had moved to No.630 King&rsquo;s Road some time after 1
2 CONC 881.</p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal">Little is known about Eliza; James's will was altered to take account of this second marriage.</p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal">James died in 1907, age 92, and was bu
2 CONC ried in the family grave with Fanny. From the Obituary again: "Deceased was very popular amongst the inhabitants of Sand's End, he being a biggish man in his way and was locally known as The King of S
2 CONC and's End."</p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal">A second obituary, possibly from The Star, focuses much more on his political activities with considerable detail, including his presence at the opening of n
2 CONC ew council offices in Fulham Palace Road with a foundation stone which bears his name on which occasion he was presented with a trowel which he treasured. The obituary continues "A thorough Radical, o
2 CONC f the old-fashioned type, he threw himself wholeheartedly into the affairs of the local Liberal Party, and they, recognising in him a strong man, quickly made him one of their leaders. As one of the c
2 CONC hairmen of districts in the days of the old Borough he was a stern and resourceful fighter and an excellent leader and Sir Charles Dilke with whom he was on terms of close friendship, valued him as on
2 CONC e of the best of his supporters.&nbsp; Indeed, one of Mr Schofield's most cherished possessions was a beautiful ring with which Chelsea's quondam M.P. presented him in recognition of his yeoman servic
2 CONC e to the Radical Cause."</p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal"><strong>JAMES SCHOFIELD&rsquo;S WILL</strong></p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal">The will is comprised of Documents dated 15th August 1884, 23rd Dec
2 CONC ember 1889, 31st August 1891, 7th June 1895, and 29th March 1898. The will lists upwards of 45 houses to be left to his wife Fanny, and on her death divided betweentheir children. As it happened, she 
2 CONC was to die before him hence, over the years, several amendments were made. One specific request is that all his propoerty shall not be sold or mortgaged by his wife, children or grandchildren during t
2 CONC heir lifetimes.</p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal">Bequests to other family members:</p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal">His brother John Schofield is to receive an annuity of &pound;20 per annum to be paid we
2 CONC ekly</p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal">His sister-in-law (Fanny's sister) Mary Ann Standage nee Wyatt, &pound;10, and her son James Standage &pound;10</p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal">His wife's niece Mary
2 CONC  Ann Buller (wife of Buller theBuilder) &pound;10</p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal">His wife's brother William Wyatt &pound;10</p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal">His wife's niece Elizabeth Ferris (sister of 
2 CONC Mary Ann Buller) &pound;10</p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal">Peterborough Benevolent Society &pound;10</p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal">His niece Elizabeth Pott, wife of George Pott, Draper of Congleton &p
2 CONC ound;10</p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal">He appears then to say that these annuities are to be paid for life to the recipients named, and that the money is to be provided by his sons and daughters, sons
2 CONC  and daughters-in-law, and their children in equal shares.</p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal">The Executors were his wife, his natural son William James Schofield and his son James Schofield. (The distinc
2 CONC tion refers to the fact that his elder son was born before his marriage, as was his second child Fanny Elizabeth, and all the other 13 children were legitimate. He was specifying that all his children
2 CONC  were to be treated equally.)</p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal">The will was witnessed by two neighbours and tenants Henry Drury, Grocer, and Matthew Bateman of 632 and 630 Kings Road respectively.</p></
2 CONC p><p><p class="MsoNormal">The first&nbsp; codicil in 1889, appears to apportion to his children various other properties he must have acquired after the original will was made.</p></p><p><p class="Mso
2 CONC Normal">The second and third codicils in 1891 and 1895 respectively, further properties bequeathed to several of his children.</p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal">The fourth codicil, 1898, was made shortly
2 CONC  after his marriage to Eliza, his second wife, contains bequests to her and her children of Brittania Cottage, 10 Britannia Road, and numbers 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, and 7 Sothern Road, King's Road, Fulham,
2 CONC  plus all his furniture, pictures, plate and utensils.</p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal">He also leaves to his grandson George Herbert Schofield, 3rd son ofWilliam James Schofield the freehold house&nbsp
2 CONC ; and shop 1A "next door to the Old Rose Beer Shop, Factory Lane". (George, a plumber, appears in the 1911 census living with his wife and 3 children at 20 Kelvedon Road, Fulham.)</p></p><p><p class="
2 CONC MsoNormal">The Will was proved 15th February 1908, Gross value being &pound;31,543/2/8d; net value of personal estate &pound;26,854/11/2d.</p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal">Some time after his death, Eli
2 CONC za Schofield moved to 10 Britannia Road, where the 1911 census finds her aged 75 and living with her unmarried sister Sarah Ann Wilson age 77. Both were born in Darenth, Kent to gamekeeper father Jame
2 CONC s Willson. (The 1851 census for the Wilson Family lists parents James Wilson age 44, Agricultural Labourer, Wife Ann age 43, Children: James 21, Margaret 19,&nbsp; Sarah 17, George 7, Emma 5, Ellen 3,
2 CONC  and Susan 4 months. Presumably Eliza at 15 had already left home by then).</p></p><p><p class="MsoNormal">Jenny Armour has a copy of the will from which this information was taken. A photo copy of th
2 CONC e 7 closely typed pages can be made on request.&nbsp;</p></p><p><p>&nbsp;</p></p><p><div>Jim Boutwood's explanation of the photo of James and Eliza:</div></p><div>"Our mutual ancestor was reading The 
2 CONC Star because that was the radical paper of the period and he was a great radical. I have got some very small snapshots of his son James, he from whom we are all descended. I expect that you have also 
2 CONC got some but if not I will copy them and send them on. They are all circa 1932, soon after my parents married. Both Pip (my eldest sister) and I can remember him or rather I can actually remember him 
2 CONC and Pip can remember all the plants in his flat where he lived after great grandma died. I bore the pants off people telling them (truthfully) that I have sat on the lap of someone who went to the Gre
2 CONC at Exhibition."</div>
