2 CONC rce has his father as Johann Wendel Georg Trout Found book "250 year history of my Trout family" by Geo. E. Trout.  Descendants of Johann Wendel George Traut (1689-1760) of Kleinfischingen, Landau, Ge
2 CONC rmany, who came to America in 1738.  He was married (l) to Maria Appolonia Steinlin, with whom he had seven children born between 1723 and 1738.  He settled in Strasburg Township of Lancaster County, 
2 CONC Pennsylvania, where in 1739 he married his second wife, Maria Magdalena Walter (1717-1760).  They had seven children born between 1739 and 1749.  Descendants and family members live in Pennsylvania,  
2 CONC                     Tennessee, Missoui and elsewhere.  See Trout Family History Book. The distinguished name of Trout, with its various forms, according to Harrison, the famous authority on the etymol
2 CONC ogy of surnames, means "beloved"  or "dear friend", from the middle high German and the old high German "trut".  We can perhaps trace our English word true to the same root...Shiploads of German peopl
2 CONC e left for America during the years of 1709-1712.  As most of these people came from Rhenish or Palatine, the name "Palatina" was applied indiscriminately to all of these immigrants, although some cam
2 CONC e from neighboring territories as well. Walter Knittle, in his book, Early Palatina Emigration, list the following bearing the Trout surname, who came to this country and landed in New York:  John Tra
2 CONC ut and two sons."</p>
