1 NOTE Brethren Trout Line--early 1700s Trouts<p></p><p>Brethren Trout Line--early 1700s Trouts</p><p>http://genforum.genealogy.com/trout/messages/815.html</p><p>Bottom of Form</p><p></p><p>The Brethren Trou
2 CONC t (Traut)</p><p>by Noel Trout, © 2000</p><p>Date: November 23, 2000 at 09:43:13</p><p>xmascat1@aol.com</p><p></p><p>Upon investigating early TROUT family origins in America, descendants</p><p>can typ
2 CONC ically trace their family back to either one of two seminal</p><p>TROUT lines. The most well-known and documented line is the Wendel</p><p>TRAUT line, which arrived in America in 1738. One of the most
2 CONC </p><p>scholarly and source-supported books I have read on this particular</p><p>line is the book 250 Year History of my Trout Family. This book was</p><p>written by George Egbert Trout (1913-1999). I
2 CONC  was able to purchase one</p><p>of the last remaining copies before the author passed away. At that</p><p>time, his grandson-Matthew Curtis-posted a message on the Trout</p><p>Genealogical Forum, "I h
2 CONC ave the last 30 copies of his book and I will</p><p>be selling them for the family. Please e-mail me directly if you are</p><p>interested" (mattnmona@earthlink.net). The other TROUT line, and the</p><
2 CONC p>focus of this essay, is the less well-known Brethren TRAUT line, which</p><p>arrived in America in 1719. (Author’s note: I will switch back and</p><p>forth between TRAUT, the original German varia
2 CONC tion of the surname, and</p><p>TROUT, the Americanized variation of the surname).</p><p></p><p>First, I will give some background on the other line-the Wendel TRAUT</p><p>line. According to the aforem
2 CONC entioned book by George E. TROUT, the</p><p>Wendel TRAUT line begins with the patriarch himself, his full name</p><p>being Johann Wendel George TRAUT (1689-1760). He immigrated to</p><p>America, arriv
2 CONC ing in Philadelphia in 1738. He brought with him four</p><p>daughters and at least three sons: Hans George (b. 1725), Hans</p><p>Nicklaus (1727-1753), and Hans Michael (1730-1780). They all settled</p
2 CONC ><p>into the Strasburg Township area of Lancaster County, Pennsylvania. In</p><p>1752, two of his sons-George and Niclaus-left Lancaster County and</p><p>moved to Virginia. Niclaus moved to Augusta Co
2 CONC unty and was</p><p>accidentally killed by a shotgun blast shortly thereafter. George</p><p>moved to Rockingham County, leaving descendants in the Roanoke area,</p><p>and he may have eventually made it
2 CONC  to North Carolina. The third</p><p>son-Michael-stayed in Lancaster County until after his father’s death.</p><p>Around 1771 he and his family moved to Frederick County, Maryland.</p><p>Wendel TRAUT
2 CONC ’s first wife had died before the family came to America</p><p>so a year after his arrival, he married another woman in the Strasburg</p><p>Township. They had at least four daughters and two sons: J
2 CONC ohan Paul</p><p>(1739-1794) and Wendel II (1743-1820). It looks like Johan Paul stayed</p><p>in Lancaster County while Wendel II moved to York County,</p><p>Pennsylvania. Finally, it must be noted tha
2 CONC t the patriarch, Wendel I,</p><p>had a cousin who had immigrated to America prior to him in 1733. His</p><p>name was Hans Martin TRAUT (b. 1677) and he settled in Berks County,</p><p>Pennsylvania. He 
2 CONC brought with him at least three daughters and two</p><p>sons: Johan Debalt (1706-1738) and John Henry (1718-1746). The latter</p><p>son ended up moving to Frederick County, Maryland, just like his</p>
2 CONC <p>half-brother Michael. All of Wendel’s and Hans Martin’s children had</p><p>their own children in the areas noted above, and this TRAUT family</p><p>began to spread throughout Pennsylvania and V
2 CONC irginia.</p><p></p><p>While Wendel’s family is more well-documented, there is another TROUT</p><p>family that arrived earlier. This is the family that is referred to in</p><p>the 1903 book, Some Vir
2 CONC ginia Families by Hugh Milton McIlhany, Jr.</p><p>This book is one of the earliest and most well-known TROUT family</p><p>history books, and gives many details about descendants from this</p><p>other 
2 CONC TROUT family. However, the book cannot pinpoint the exact</p><p>origins of this family, only stating that, "From the traditions</p><p>preserved in several branches of the Trout family today, it would 
2 CONC seem</p><p>that many years before the Revolutionary War three brothers,</p><p>Lutherans, fleeing from religious persecution in Germany, emigrated</p><p>from the neighborhoood of Frankfort-on-the-Main 
2 CONC and settled in</p><p>Germantown, Philidelphia." The book goes on to state that family</p><p>tradition has it that the three brothers’ names were Nathaniel,</p><p>Daniel, and Jeremiah. The author sta
2 CONC tes that while the traditional</p><p>account of this family’s history is "in the main correct…the names of</p><p>the original immigrants have been handed down inaccurately." Instead,</p><p>the nam
2 CONC es of the three brothers were John Balthazar (aka Baltzer),</p><p>George, and Jeremias Trout, and the book picks up with an account of</p><p>their lives and descendants beginning around 1740.</p><p></
2 CONC p><p>If one were only to rely upon the well-known text Some Virginia</p><p>Families, it would seem that the exact details of this family’s</p><p>genesis in America have been lost to antiquity. Howev
2 CONC er, there are</p><p>other, less well-known texts that exist, which I believe give a more</p><p>detailed and accurate account of just who these initial TROUTs were.</p><p>These books detail the history
2 CONC  of the Church of the Brethren, which</p><p>began in Germany in 1708. The Church of the Brethren (also known as</p><p>the "Dunkers") was what could be considered an outlaw sect in Germany</p><p>at the
2 CONC  time. As a result of great persecution, 20 members of this</p><p>small religious congregation left for America in 1719, eight of whom</p><p>were TRAUTs, and they landed in Philadelphia, settling in G
2 CONC ermantown.</p><p>One of the earliest books that detailed this church’s history is</p><p>Martin Brumbaugh’s A History of the German Baptist Brethren in Europe</p><p>and America, published in 1899. 
2 CONC Another Brethren church historian</p><p>whose books include these earliest TROUT ancestors is Donald F.</p><p>Durnbaugh (see source footnotes for specific texts). Finally, a TROUT</p><p>descendant and
2 CONC  another Brethren church historian and author is Ellen</p><p>Louise Larick, whom I have gotten to know and found very helpful and</p><p>knowledgeable (she has even traveled to Germany to research the<
2 CONC /p><p>origins of this TROUT family; more on that further below).</p><p></p><p>According to these various texts about the history of the Church of</p><p>the Brethren, of the eight TRAUT family members 
2 CONC who made the trek to</p><p>America in 1719 with 12 other Brethren congregants, the adult men</p><p>consisted of three brothers. Their names were Johann Henrich, Georg</p><p>Balthasar, and Jeremias TRA
2 CONC UT. The names of these three brothers as</p><p>recorded in the Church of the Brethren history is strikingly similar</p><p>to those mentioned in the McIlhany’s Some Virginia Families book. All</p><p>
2 CONC three brothers were from Frankenthal, Germany.[1] Again, this is very</p><p>similar to the fuzzy traditional account documented by McIlhany</p><p>("Frankfort-on-the-Main"), as is the fact that the thr
2 CONC ee brothers</p><p>immigrated here in the pursuit of religious freedom. These original</p><p>three TRAUT brothers settled in the vicinity of Philadelphia County,</p><p>Pennsylvania. However, while the 
2 CONC details of the very initial history</p><p>of this family coming to America are preserved, once they arrived in</p><p>America it becomes very difficult to determine who their offspring</p><p>were. Appa
2 CONC rently, many of their children bore the same name as the</p><p>original three brothers, probably in honor of each other. It becomes</p><p>impossible to tell, for example, when a land grant states that
2 CONC  Baltzer</p><p>TROUT owned property in Germantown, Philadelphia in 1734,[3] whether</p><p>this was the original Baltzer or one of the many descendants who</p><p>retained the Baltzer namesake. Further 
2 CONC complicating this puzzle is the</p><p>confusion over Johann Henrich or John Henry (see further below). In</p><p>some ways it appears that the three brothers may have been the</p><p>children of a man b
2 CONC y the same name. One day I hope to stumble upon</p><p>some new pieces of information that will shed light on this mystery.</p><p></p><p>Nevertheless, let me go back to the beginning in Germany and the
2 CONC n onto</p><p>Philadelphia, and I will give as full account of the origins of this</p><p>TROUT line as I can. Some of this comes from the aforementioned</p><p>Brethren history texts while other informa
2 CONC tion is pieced together from</p><p>other sources (see footnotes to determine what comes from where). Not</p><p>surprising for genealogical research, not all of the pieces fit.</p><p>However, I wanted 
2 CONC to give as full account as possible of all the</p><p>information that I could find in hopes that someone else with other or</p><p>new information might be able to eventually put things together in</p>
2 CONC <p>their right or complete order.</p><p></p><p>To start off with, in Germany during the late 1600s and early 1700s,</p><p>there was the state-mandated form of Christianity and then there were</p><p>ot
2 CONC her illegal denominations or "Pietists." One such group was the</p><p>Anabaptists. They believed that infant baptism was not valid; an</p><p>adult, in the understanding of his or her own mature mind, 
2 CONC must make a</p><p>decision to follow Christ and then be baptized. Thus came about their</p><p>name "Anabaptist": in other words, re-baptizers. As uncontroversial as</p><p>it may sound today, this was 
2 CONC a crime punishable by hard labor, prison,</p><p>or banishment. Part of the problem was that all of these sects were a</p><p>challenge to the church-state’s prevailing viewpoints and consequently</p>
2 CONC <p>their power. While certain groups, like the "Inspirationists," made</p><p>dramatic prophecies in which they "denounced the wickedness of the</p><p>authorities,"[4] the Brethren were not as exciting
2 CONC . They were</p><p>considered merely troublesome by the authorities "only because of</p><p>their belief in the necessity of baptism by immersion."[4]</p><p></p><p>In 1705 a Johann Henrich TRAUT was one
2 CONC  of four citizens of Lambsheim</p><p>(near Frankenthal), Germany, imprisoned for their refusal to swear</p><p>oaths of allegience.[1] In 1706, a Johannes TRAUT was accused of</p><p>Pietism in Lambshei
2 CONC m Rheinland/Pfalz and sentenced to cleaning the</p><p>town’s ditches.[2] This may have been the same Johann Henrich TRAUT</p><p>that was one of our original three brothers or it may have been the</p
2 CONC ><p>father of all three. Records show that he was married to Anna</p><p>Katharina and had two sons, aged 10 and 6 at the time;[2] a daughter</p><p>and a son-in-law also were living with him.[1] At any
2 CONC  rate, some</p><p>records state that he sold his home in Lambsheim in 1709 and went to</p><p>London, England.[1] He was 40 years old at this time.[2] Later on, he</p><p>sailed to New York and then set
2 CONC tled into the Dublin Township of</p><p>Montgomery C</p>
