4 CONC ull information.&amp;lt;br&amp;gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Additional information: LifeSketch:Braxton never married.  He was educated at the University of West Virginia, from which he graduated in 1893 wit
4 CONC h a degree of Bachelor of Science.  He studied law at the University of Virginia under Dr. John B. Minor, and settled at Cleveland, Ohio, in the practice of his profession, under Judge J. H. Collins, 
4 CONC Chief Counsel of the B&amp;O Railroad.   While at college he won distinction as an author and orator.  He received at the University of West Virginia the Richard Randalph Mac Mahon prize on his essay 
4 CONC on the &quot;Religion of Shakespeare&quot;. Among his writings was a very complete essay on the John Brown raid.  He was the author of numerous articles essays and poems.  He died at the early age of 
4 CONC twenty-seven from pneumonia, and was mourned by a devoted family and large circle of friends and admirers.  He is buried by the side of his parents in the Davenport lot in the Edgehill Cemetery at Cha
4 CONC rles Town, West Virginia.  His tombstone, erected by his father bears thee inscription:  &quot;With thee, my son perished many hopes.&quot;
