0 @S500002@ SOUR
1 TITL 1900 United States Federal Census
1 PUBL MyHeritage
1 TEXT Federal census takers were asked to record information about every person who was in each household on the census day. A census taker might have visited a house on a later date, but the information he
2 CONC  collected was supposed to be about the people who were in the house on the census day. The basic census enumeration unit was the county. Each county was divided into enumeration districts, one for ea
2 CONC ch enumerator. The completed forms were sent to the Commerce Department's Census Office in Washington, D.C.Federal censuses are usually reliable, depending on the knowledge of the informant and the ca
2 CONC re of the census enumerator. Information may have been given to a census taker by any member of the family or by a neighbor. Some information may have been incorrect or deliberately falsified.
1 _TYPE Collection
1 _MEDI 10131
1 RIN MH:S500002
0 @S500003@ SOUR
1 TITL FamilySearch Family Tree
1 PUBL MyHeritage
1 TEXT The FamilySearch Family Tree is published by MyHeritage under license from FamilySearch International, the largest genealogy organization in the world. FamilySearch is a nonprofit organization sponsor
2 CONC ed by The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (Mormon Church).
